    <language>en_US</language>
    <keyword>corrcoef</keyword>
    <short_description>Correlation coefficients</short_description>
    <syntax>
        <syntax_item>R = corrcoef(M)</syntax_item>
    </syntax>
    <param_input>
        <param_input_item>
            <param_name>M</param_name>
            <param_description>a vector or matrix</param_description>
        </param_input_item>
    </param_input>
    <param_output>
        <param_output_item>
            <param_name>R</param_name>
            <param_description
      >Correlation coefficients of M.</param_description>
        </param_output_item>
    </param_output>
    <description>
        <p>
            <b
      >R = corrcoef(M)</b> returns the matrix of correlation coefficients for <b
      >M</b>, where the columns of <b
      >M</b> represent random variables and the rows represent observations.
        </p>
        <p>The Pearson correlation coefficient between variables</p>
        <latex>X</latex>
        <p>and</p>
        <latex>Y</latex>
        <p>is:</p>
        <latex
    >r_{XY} = \frac{\text{cov}(X,Y)}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar{x})(y_i - \bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar{x})^2 \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \bar{y})^2}}</latex>
        <p>where</p>
        <latex>\bar{x}</latex>
        <p>and</p>
        <latex>\bar{y}</latex>
        <p>are the sample means, and</p>
        <latex>\sigma_X</latex>
        <p>,</p>
        <latex>\sigma_Y</latex>
        <p>are the standard deviations.</p>
        <p
    >The correlation coefficient ranges from -1 to +1, where -1 indicates perfect negative correlation, +1 indicates perfect positive correlation, and 0 indicates no linear correlation.</p>
    </description>
